Thousands of people <a href="https://link.cfr.org/click/30768797.15899/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMy8wMy8wOC93b3JsZC9ldXJvcGUvZ2VvcmdpYS1wcm90ZXN0cy1mb3JlaWduLWFnZW50cy1sYXcuaHRtbD91dG1fc291cmNlPWRhaWx5YnJpZWY/5e137cf6ecf12a133a10a3b7Bc390d11c" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">braved tear gas and water cannons (<em>NYT</em>)</a> to rally in Georgia’s capital, Tbilisi, yesterday in protest of a bill that would require all organizations that receive more than 20 percent of their funding from abroad to register as “foreign agents.” The bill <a href="https://link.cfr.org/click/30768797.15899/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucG9saXRpY28uZXUvYXJ0aWNsZS9nZW9yZ2lhLXByb3Rlc3RzLWV1LXJ1c3NpYS11a3JhaW5lLXdhci10YmlsaXNpLXJpb3QtcG9saWNlLWZvcmVpZ24tYWdlbnRzLWxhdy8_dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1kYWlseWJyaWVm/5e137cf6ecf12a133a10a3b7B41f0762d" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">passed (<em>Politico</em>)</a> an initial congressional vote yesterday and has the backing of the ruling Georgian Dream party. It <a href="https://link.cfr.org/click/30768797.15899/aHR0cHM6Ly9reWl2aW5kZXBlbmRlbnQuY29tL25ld3MtZmVlZC9wcm90ZXN0cy1lcnVwdC1pbi1nZW9yZ2lhLW92ZXIta3JlbWxpbi1pbnNwaXJlZC1mb3JlaWduLWFnZW50LWxlZ2lzbGF0aW9uP3V0bV9zb3VyY2U9ZGFpbHlicmllZg/5e137cf6ecf12a133a10a3b7B5e722564" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">resembles Russian legislation (<em>Kyiv Independent</em>)</a> that has been used to target civil society groups. 
</p><p> </p><p>
Georgian President Salome Zourabichvili called the bill “dictated by Moscow” and signaled that it could jeopardize Georgia’s potential accession to the European Union (EU), which it applied to join last year. Polls show that 85 percent of Georgians support EU membership, and some protesters have waved EU flags. Hundreds of them returned today for a fresh round of demonstrations.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr>
</tbody></table><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Analysis</p></td></tr></tbody></table><table><tbody><tr><td><p>
“A growing number of Georgians <a href="https://link.cfr.org/click/30768797.15899/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucG9saXRpY28uZXUvYXJ0aWNsZS9nZW9yZ2lhLXByb3Rlc3RzLWV1LXJ1c3NpYS11a3JhaW5lLXdhci10YmlsaXNpLXJpb3QtcG9saWNlLWZvcmVpZ24tYWdlbnRzLWxhdy8_dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1kYWlseWJyaWVm/5e137cf6ecf12a133a10a3b7C41f0762d" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">fear that their government is moving closer to Moscow</a> under Georgian Dream, which has been in power since 2012. The party’s founder, former chairman and ex-Prime Minister Bidzina Ivanishvili, has close ties to Russia, where he built his fortune in the 1990s,” <em>Politico</em>’s Nicolas Camut and Zoya Sheftalovich write.
</p><p><br/>
“The West <a href="https://link.cfr.org/click/30768797.15899/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZm9yZWlnbmFmZmFpcnMuY29tL2dlb3JnaWEvbWFrZS1ydXNzaWEtcGF5P3V0bV9zb3VyY2U9ZGFpbHlicmllZg/5e137cf6ecf12a133a10a3b7B81b1bcea" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">cannot forget the lessons of [Russia’s 2008 invasion of Georgia]</a>: it must remember the dangers of accommodating [Russian President Vladimir Putin] or another Russian dictator,” the Foreign Policy Research Institute’s Vasil Sikharulidze writes for <em>Foreign Affairs. </em></p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table>
